<head>
<title>@HI{{ga}} (particle)</title>
<link rel="stylesheet" type="text/css" href="japanese.css"/>
<meta http-equiv="Content-Type" content="text/html; charset=utf-8">
</head>

<body>

<h1>@HI{{ga}} (particle)</h1>

<h2> Formation </h2>

<ol>
<li> @N{{}} @HI{{ha}} ... 
</ol>

<h2> Definition </h2>

<p>
<strong>@HI{{ga}}</strong> is a particle which indicates the subject, or sometimes the object, of a verb
or adjective. For uses of @HI{{ga}} as a conjunction, see <a href="grammar-ga-conjunction.html">here</a>.
</p>

<p>
When a subject is first introduced it is marked by <strong>@HI{{ga}}</strong>, unless it is the topic, in which
case it is marked by @HI{{ha}}. Consider the following typical opening for a folktale.

<table class="sentence" border=0>
  <tr class="jp"> <td>
      @HI{{@KJ{{once*upon*a*time^noma^one^person}}noojisann<strong>ga</strong>@KJ{{dwell}}ndeimashita.}}
  </td> </tr>
  <tr class="jp"> <td>
      @HI{{ojisanhatotemo@KJ{{poverty^destitution}}deshita.}}
  </td> </tr>
  <tr class="en"> <td>
      Once upon a time there lived an old man.
  </td> </tr>
  <tr class="en"> <td>
      The old man was very poor.
  </td> </tr>
</table>

In the first sentence the old man is the subject but not the topic, and so is marked by <strong>@HI{{ga}}</strong>.
In the second sentence he is presented as the topic and further information about him is added; in this
sentence he is marked by @HI{{ha}}.
</p>

<p>
<strong>@HI{{ga}}</strong> is used with verbs such as @HI{{aru}}, @HI{{iru}}, @HI{{gozaimasu}} and @HI{{irassharu}}.
If a contrast is being presented then @HI{{ha}} can replaced <strong>@HI{{ga}}</strong>.

<table class="sentence" border=0>
  <tr class="jp"> <td>
      @HI{{asoko ni @KJ{{private}}no@KT{{bo-rupenn}}<strong>ga</strong>arimasuka.}}
  </td> </tr>
  <tr class="en"> <td>
      Is that my ballpoint pen over there?
  </td> </tr>
</table>
</p>

<p>
@HI{{ha}} is used if information is being presented about a subject that has already been identified.
</p>

<p>
<strong>@HI{{ga}}</strong> indicates the subject of the predicate.

<table class="sentence" border=0>
  <tr class="jp"> <td>
      @HI{{asoko ni @KJ{{cherry}}<strong>ga</strong> @KJ{{blossom}}teimasu.}}
  </td> </tr>
  <tr class="en"> <td>
      Over there the cherry trees are blooming.
  </td> </tr>
</table>
</p>

<p>
<strong>@HI{{ga}}</strong> indicates the subject of an intransitive verb.

<table class="sentence" border=0>
  <tr class="jp"> <td>
      @HI{{@KJ{{door}}<strong>ga</strong> @KJ{{open}}kimashita.}}
  </td> </tr>
  <tr class="en"> <td>
      The door opened.
  </td> </tr>
</table>
</p>

<p>
<strong>@HI{{ga}}</strong> indicates the subject of the sentence when new, previously unknown, information is presented.

<table class="sentence" border=0>
  <tr class="jp"> <td>
      @HI{{kochira<strong>ga</strong> @KJ{{mountain^rice*field}}sann desu.}}
  </td> </tr>
  <tr class="en"> <td>
      This is Mr. Yamada. <em>(a personal introduction)</em>
  </td> </tr>
</table>
</p>

<p>
<strong>@HI{{ga}}</strong> is used with interrogative words in questions, both in general questions and when asking for
a choice.

<ol>
<li>
<table class="sentence" border=0>
  <tr class="jp"> <td>
      @HI{{dare<strong>ga</strong>@KJ{{one^turn^early}}kukimashitaka.}}
  </td> </tr>
  <tr class="en"> <td>
      Who arrived first?
  </td> </tr>
</table>
</p>
<li>
<table class="sentence" border=0>
  <tr class="jp"> <td>
      @HI{{suhitotenpuratodochira<strong>ga</strong>@KJ{{fond}}kidesuka.}}
  </td> </tr>
  <tr class="en"> <td>
      Which do you like better, sushi or tempura?
  </td> </tr>
</table>
</ol>
<p>
<strong>@HI{{ga}}</strong> indicates the subject of a <a href="grammar-relative-clause.html">relative clause</a>. Note
that @HI{{no}} can often perform this function too.

<table class="sentence" border=0>
  <tr class="jp"> <td>
      @HI{{@KJ{{before^week^private}}<strong>ga</strong>@KJ{{see}}ta@KJ{{reflect^brush-stroke}}hatsumaranakatta.}}
  </td> </tr>
  <tr class="en"> <td>
      The film I saw last week was broing.
  </td> </tr>
</table>
</p>

<p>
<strong>@HI{{ga}}</strong> indicates the subject of a clause ending in @HI{{ka}}.

<table class="sentence" border=0>
  <tr class="jp"> <td>
      @HI{{naze@KJ{{he}}<strong>ga</strong>sonnnakotowoyattaka, wakarimasenn.}}
  </td> </tr>
  <tr class="en"> <td>
      I don't know why he did something like that.
  </td> </tr>
</table>
</p>

<p>
<strong>@HI{{ga}}</strong> indicates the subject of a subordinate or conditional clause when it differs from the
subject of the main clause.

<table class="sentence" border=0>
  <tr class="jp"> <td>
      @HI{{@KJ{{mother}}<strong>ga</strong>@KJ{{day^book}}nikuru@KJ{{in*front}}ni, kono@KJ{{section^roof}}wokireini
      @KJ{{sweep^exclude}}shinakereba naranai.}}
  </td> </tr>
  <tr class="en"> <td>
      Before my mother comes to Japan I have to make this room nice and clean.
  </td> </tr>
</table>
</p>

<p>
<strong>@HI{{ga}}</strong> indicates the object of verbs of ability, such as @HI{{dekiru}} and @HI{{wakaru}}, and of the
<a href="grammar-verb-use-of-potential.html">potential</a> form of verbs.

<table class="sentence" border=0>
  <tr class="jp"> <td>
      @HI{{@KJ{{africa^section}}sanha @KT{{gorufu}}<strong>ga</strong> dekimasu.}}
  </td> </tr>
  <tr class="en"> <td>
      Abe can play golf.
  </td> </tr>
</table>
</p>

<p>
<strong>@HI{{ga}}</strong> indicates the object of verbs of sensation, such as @HI{{mieru}} and @HI{{kikoeru}} as well as
@HI{{suru}} in some cases.

<table class="sentence" border=0>
  <tr class="jp"> <td>
      @HI{{kokokara@KJ{{wealth^gentleman^mountain}}<strong>ga</strong>@KJ{{see}}emasu.}}
  </td> </tr>
  <tr class="en"> <td>
      Mt. Fuji can be seen from here.
  </td> </tr>
</table>
</p>

<p>
<strong>@HI{{ga}}</strong> indicates the object of verbs of necessity.

<table class="sentence" border=0>
  <tr class="jp"> <td>
      @HI{{@KJ{{private}}hao@KJ{{gold}}<strong>ga</strong>@KJ{{need}}ru.}}
  </td> </tr>
  <tr class="en"> <td>
      I need money.
  </td> </tr>
</table>
</p>

<p>
<strong>@HI{{ga}}</strong> indicates the object of adjectives of desire.

<table class="sentence" border=0>
  <tr class="jp"> <td>
      @HI{{@KJ{{time^interval}}too@KJ{{gold}}<strong>ga</strong>@KJ{{longing}}shii.}}
  </td> </tr>
  <tr class="en"> <td>
      I want time and money.
  </td> </tr>
</table>
</p>

<p>
<strong>@HI{{ga}}</strong> indicates the object of verbs and adjectives of emotion.

<table class="sentence" border=0>
  <tr class="jp"> <td>
      @HI{{@KT{{jonn}}sanhanattou<strong>ga</strong>@KJ{{dislike}}idesu.}}
  </td> </tr>
  <tr class="en"> <td>
      John doesn't like @HI{{nattou}}.
  </td> </tr>
</table>
</p>

<p>
<strong>@HI{{ga}}</strong> indicates the object of verbs of ability.

<table class="sentence" border=0>
  <tr class="jp"> <td>
      @HI{{@KJ{{new}}shii@KJ{{neck^inter-}}ha,@KJ{{haiku^phrase}}<strong>ga</strong>@KJ{{above^hand}}dasoudesu.}}
  </td> </tr>
  <tr class="en"> <td>
      The new prime minister is said to be good at haiku.
  </td> </tr>
</table>
</p>

